"Katherine Helmond, who starred as memorable mom Mona Robinson on \u201CWho\u2019s the Boss\u201D and on soap opera series \u201CSoap\u201D, died on Feb. 23, 2019; the 89-year-old\u2019s death was first reported on March 1. While Helmond was a memorable face on television and on the big screen, starring in \u201CEverybody Loves Raymond\u201D and \u201890s sitcom \u201CCoach\u201D, as well as 1985\u2019s \u201CBrazil\u201D and 1998\u2019s \u201CFear and Loathing in Las Vegas\u201D, she was also no stranger to Broadway. Helmond earned a Tony in 1973 for her role in \u201CThe Great God Brown\u201D and a Drama Critics Award for \u201CThe House of Blue Leaves\u201D, among other roles. (Evan Agostini / Getty Images)",

"Andre Previn, the pianist, composer and conductor whose broad reach took in the worlds of Hollywood, jazz and classical music, died on Feb. 28, 2019, in his Manhattan home. He was 89. He was married five times, the third with Mia Farrow with whom he remained close his entire life. Among his many awards and high honors, Previn won four Academy Awards for his original music, 10 Grammy awards and Lifetime Achievement Awards from the Kennedy Center, the London Symphony Orchestra and the Recording Academy. Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II named him honorary Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire in 1996. (Anonymous / AP)",

"Stanley Donen, director of some of Hollywood's most cherished musicals and films during the Golden Age of Hollywood, died from heart failure on Feb. 21, 2019 in New York City. He was 94. Donen received the Lifetime Achievement Award at the 1998 Academy Awards for his tremendous accomplishments including \"Singin' in the Rain\" (1952) co-directed with Gene Kelly, \"On the Town\" (1949) and \"Two for the Road\" (1967), among many others. Donen is seen here at the International Film Festival on May 10, 1984, in Cannes, France. (RALPH GATTI / AFP/Getty Images)",

"Brody Stevens, a beloved comedian in the Los Angeles community, died on Feb. 22, 2019, at his home in Los Angeles, from an apparent suicide. He was 48. Stevens is known for his appearances on many series on Comedy Central such as \"Chelsea Lately\" and \"Kroll Show\" and in movies like \"Due Date\" and \"The Hangover.\" In this photo, Brody Stevens performs during the Funny Or Die Oddball Comedy Festival at the Austin360 Amphitheater on Sept. 21, 2014 in Austin, Texas. (Gary Miller / Getty Images)",

"Clark Gable III, the sole grandson of screen icon Clark Gable, died on Feb. 22, 2019, from undisclosed causes at his home in Dallas, Texas. He was 30. The host of \"Cheaters,\" a reality show, he had recently completed \"Heckle,\" a comedy-drama and was currently filming \"Sunset at Dawn,\" a crime film. (Unimedia/REX/Shutterstock)",

"Jackie Shane, a soul singer who became a transgender rights pioneering musician in the 1960s, has died. The specific date and cause of her death has not been disclosed. She was 78. Originally from the South during the Jim Crow era, she relocated to Toronto, Canada and became an integral part of the nascent R&B music scene. Pictured here is the album cover released by Numero Group showing Jackie Shane's \u201CAny Other Way,\u201D which was nominated for Best Historical Album GRAMMY on Feb. 10, 2019. (Numero Group via AP)",

"Dominick Argento is at his piano in his Minneapolis, Minn., home on May 5, 1975, after learning he had been awarded the Pulitzer Prize for music for \"From the Diary of Virginia Woolf.\" Argento died on Feb. 20, 2019, in Minneapolis, Minn., according to Carol Ann Cheung, a spokeswoman for his music publisher, Boosey & Hawkes. He was 91. Argento is best-known for writing musical compositions sparked by the works and lives of writers Charles Dickens, Henry James and Elizabeth Barrett Browning to name a few. (AP)",

"Guitarist Peter Tork, a member of the famed 1960s pop group The Monkees, died on Feb. 21, 2019; he was 77 and had lived with a form of tongue cancer for the last ten years. Tork, along with the other members of the group, rose to fame during the sixties as television\u2019s answer to The Beatles in \u201CA Hard Day\u2019s Night\u201D. The group soon achieved their own successful level of fame during their 1966-1971 run. Over the years, Tork has formed and toured with his own groups, including Shoe Suede Blues and The Peter Tork Project. (Matthew Eisman / Getty Images)",

"Former Brooklyn Dodgers pitcher and baseball great Don Newcombe died on Feb. 19, 2019 at the age of 92. Newcombe was revered throughout his 10 year MLB career \u2013 winning four All-Star titles and a 3.56 ERA by the end \u2013 which earned him Rookie of the Year, Most Valuable Player and Cy Young Award honors, one of only two players in the history of the sport to do so. (Chris Carlson / AP)",
